{{Starbox begin | name = PSR B0943+10 }}{{Starbox observe | epoch = [[J2000.0]] | constell = [[Leo (constellation)|Leo]] | ra = {{RA|19|46|7.4}}<ref name="Zang">{{cite journal | url=http://iopscience.iop.org/1538-4357/624/2/L109/fulltext/19436.text.html | author=Zang, Bing | author2=Sanwal, Divas | author3=Pavlov, George G. | last-author-amp=yes | title=An XMM-Newton Observation of the Drifting Pulsar B0943+10| journal=Astrophysical Journal | pages=L109-L112 | date=2005|doi=10.1086/430522|arxiv = astro-ph/0503423 |bibcode = 2005ApJ...624L.109Z }}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|+09|51|54}}<ref name="Zang"/> | appmag_v = }}{{Starbox astrometry | dist_pc = 0.63 ± 0.10 k<ref name="Zang"/> }}{{Starbox character | class = [[neutron star]] | b-v = | u-b = | variable = Pulsar }}{{Starbox detail | mass = | radius = | luminosity = 1.31×10<sup>−5</sup><ref name="Zang"/> | temperature = 3.1×10<sup>5</sup><ref name="Zang"/> | metal = | rotation = 1.1 [[second|s]] | age = 5&nbsp;×&nbsp;10<sup>6</sup> }}{{Starbox reference | Simbad = PSR+B0943%2B10 }}{{Starbox end}} '''PSR B0943+10''' is a [[pulsar]] 2,000 [[light years]] from Earth<ref name="Zang"/> in the direction of the [[constellation]] of [[Leo (constellation)|Leo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130125/jsp/nation/story_16483828.jsp|title=Pune telescope spots Jekyll & Hyde puzzle in sky|author=G.S. Mudur|publisher=''The Telegraph, India''|date=January 25, 2013|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref>
==Description== The pulsar is estimated to be 5 million years old, which is relatively old for a pulsar.<ref name="Astronomy.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronomy.com/~/link.aspx?_id=418c617f-ff97-4a7c-b34b-6f6c72ae6049|title=Baffling pulsar leaves astronomers in the dark|author=ESA|publisher=''[[Astronomy.com]]''|date=January 25, 2013|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref> It has a rotational period of 1.1 seconds and emits both radio waves and [[X-rays]].<ref name="Space.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.space.com/19418-weird-pulsar-defies-theories.html|title=Weird Spinning Star Defies Explanation|author=Elizabeth Howell|publisher=''[[Space.com]]''|date=January 24, 2013|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref> Ongoing research at the [[University of Vermont]] discovered that the pulsar was found to flip on a roughly a few hours timescale between a radio bright mode with highly organized pulsations and a quieter mode with rather chaotic temporal structure.<ref name=Sciencedaily/><ref name=Hermsen2013/>
Moreover, the observations of the pulsar performed simultaneously with the [[European Space Agency]]'s [[XMM-Newton]] [[X-ray telescope|X-ray observatory]] and ground-based radio telescopes revealed that it exhibits variations in its X-ray emission that mimic in reverse the changes seen in radio waves—the pulsar has a weaker non-pulsing X-ray luminosity during the radio bright mode and is actually brighter during the radio quite mode emitting distinct X-ray pulses.<ref name=Hermsen2013>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hermsen | first1 = W. | last2 = Hessels | first2 = J. W. T. | last3 = Kuiper | first3 = L. | last4 = Van Leeuwen | first4 = J. | last5 = Mitra | first5 = D. | last6 = De Plaa | first6 = J. | last7 = Rankin | first7 = J. M. | last8 = Stappers | first8 = B. W. | last9 = Wright | first9 = G. A. E. | last10 = Basu | doi = 10.1126/science.1230960 | first10 = R. | last11 = Alexov | first11 = A. | last12 = Coenen | first12 = T. | last13 = Grießmeier | first13 = J. - M. | last14 = Hassall | first14 = T. E. | last15 = Karastergiou | first15 = A. | last16 = Keane | first16 = E. | last17 = Kondratiev | first17 = V. I. | last18 = Kramer | first18 = M. | last19 = Kuniyoshi | first19 = M. | last20 = Noutsos | first20 = A. | last21 = Serylak | first21 = M. | last22 = Pilia | first22 = M. | last23 = Sobey | first23 = C. | last24 = Weltevrede | first24 = P. | last25 = Zagkouris | first25 = K. | last26 = Asgekar | first26 = A. | last27 = Avruch | first27 = I. M. | last28 = Batejat | first28 = F. | last29 = Bell | first29 = M. E. | last30 = Bell | first30 = M. R. | title = Synchronous X-ray and Radio Mode Switches: A Rapid Global Transformation of the Pulsar Magnetosphere | journal = Science | volume = 339 | issue = 6118 | pages = 436–439 | year = 2013 | pmid = 23349288| pmc = |arxiv = 1302.0203 |bibcode = 2013Sci...339..436H }}</ref> Such changes can only be explained if the pulsar's magnetosphere (which may extend up to 52,000&nbsp;km from the surface) quickly switches between two extreme states.<ref name="Astronomy.com"/> The change happens on a few seconds timescale, far faster than most pulsars. Despite being one of the first pulsars discovered the mechanism for its unusual behavior is unknown.<ref name=Sciencedaily>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2013/01/130124150802.htm|title=Chameleon Pulsar Dramatically Changes the Way It Shines|author=Staff|publisher=''[[Sciencedaily.com]]''|date=January 24, 2013|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref>
A research group from [[Peking University]] in [[Beijing, China]] published a paper suggesting that the pulsar may actually be a low-mass [[quark star]].<ref name="Yue">{{cite journal | url=https://arxiv.org/pdf/astro-ph/0603468.pdf | author=Yue, Y. L. | author2=Cui, X. H. | author3=Xu, R. X. | title=Is PSR B0943+10 a low-mass quark star?| journal=Astrophysical Journal | pages=1 | date=2006 |arxiv = astro-ph/0603468v2|bibcode = 2006ApJ...649L..95Y |doi = 10.1086/508421 }}</ref>
==Planetary system==
On May of 2014 two gas giants [[extrasolar planets]] was found orbiting PSR B0943+10 <ref>[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1134%2FS1063772914110067 "Detection of regular variations in the intensity and pulse time of arrival of the anomalous pulsar PSR B0943+10".] S. A. Suleymanova and A. E. Rodin, (May 21, 2014).</ref> <ref>[http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/psr_b0943+10_c/ "The Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia Planet PSR B0943+10 c"</ref> <ref>[http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/psr_b0943+10_b/ "The Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia Planet PSR B0943+10 b"</ref>
{{OrbitboxPlanet begin | <ref> http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/psr_b0943+10_c/ "The Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia Planet PSR B0943+10 c"</ref> <ref> http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/psr_b0943+10_b/ "The Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia Planet PSR B0943+10 b"</ref> }} {{OrbitboxPlanet | exoplanet = [[PSR B0943+10b|b]] | mass = 2.8 | period = 730 | semimajor = 1.8 | eccentricity = }} {{OrbitboxPlanet | exoplanet = [[PSR B0943+10c|c]] | mass = 2.6 | period = 1460 | semimajor = 2.9 | eccentricity = }} {{Orbitbox end}}
